The Eccentric Woodland is the frontier forest south of Midgaard's Southern Wild Gate — geographically close to the city but institutionally outside its effective governance. Named during the Lantern Reforms when survey clerks assigned it a registry category acknowledging irregular terrain behavior without implying control. The woodland was a pre-institutional fog-prone verge before Midgaard formalized, navigated by shepherd-priests and bell walkers using relationship and memory rather than survey marks. Under the First Stone Accord, Midgaard claimed authority over traffic using the southern gate but disclaimed responsibility for the interior — an "escorted margin" policy that has held ever since. Clearings shift between pastoral and predatory character, game paths move or close between visits, and landmarks cannot be reliably re-located between patrol cycles. Power inside the woodland is fragmented into performative authority cells: informal path wardens selling navigation, ritual houses using oath language to legitimate rank, predator bands mimicking ritual forms, and survivor clusters in hollows and clearings. Not all predator bands are opportunistic outsiders; some originate from lapsed Rakuen guide-compact agreements whose contracts expired during disaster years, and these know route structures and cargo profiles better than any newcomer. Rakuen lies south beyond the woodland and depends on this corridor for grain supplements, medicine, and labor movement. The three Rakuen annexation petitions to Midgaard all cited woodland route instability; all three were refused.

