The Eccentric Woodland is an existential logistics problem for Rakuen—the city has no alternative
southern supply corridor. Rakuen maintains three Dispatch Houses managing guide-compact agreements
with different woodland territorial operators. The predecessor-compact problem is politically sensitive:
former path-warden operators whose contracts expired during disaster years continued exercising
territorial authority without legitimating compact, knowing Rakuen's route structures and cargo
profiles better than any newcomer. Attributing specific predation incidents to lapsed compacts would
constitute public admission that Rakuen's supply failures created the threat. All three Rakuen
annexation petitions cited woodland instability; Midgaard's refusal cited the same instability as
the reason integration was impractical—a circularity Rakuen cannot break without either resolving
the woodland problem itself or forcing Midgaard to resolve it.

